    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Why do we need this check? Is it a problem if `sendMore` gets a value in the buffered channel? I don't think it matters which one is prioritized. Either one will exit the select statement and \"return\". If `sendMore` is sent a write will happen. But if you close the connection, a write will also happen because the `<-c.sendMore` gets unblocked.\r\n\r\n```golang\r\nif c.isClosed() {\r\n\treturn\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIdk, just seems redundant. \r\n\r\nGrabbing the closed lock doesn't seem necessary because of the same argument.",
    "commit_id": "445e8b097a10998eb85e9de95af2cea1bae7d0a0",
    "created_at": "2022-07-21T13:29:40Z",
    "diff_hunk": "@@ -106,12 +106,15 @@ func (c *Channel) init() {\n \t// write operations to block once the threshold is set.\n \tc.dc.SetBufferedAmountLowThreshold(bufferedAmountLowThreshold)\n \tc.dc.OnBufferedAmountLow(func() {\n+\t\t// Grab the lock to protect the sendMore channel from being\n+\t\t// closed in between the isClosed check and the send.\n+\t\tc.closeMutex.Lock()\n+\t\tdefer c.closeMutex.Unlock()\n \t\tif c.isClosed() {\n \t\t\treturn\n \t\t}\n \t\tselect {\n \t\tcase <-c.closed:",
